      "extra": {
        "message": "Cleartext CCN in API Response - fetch_customer\n\nThe /fetch/customer endpoint returns the full credit card number in the API response without masking.\n\nImpact: Any authenticated user can retrieve full credit card numbers of any customer, enabling financial fraud.\n\nFix: Mask credit card numbers in API responses (e.g., show only last 4 digits). Implement proper authorization to restrict access.",
        "severity": "HIGH",
        "metadata": {
          "cwe": [
            "CWE-312"
          ],
          "finding_id": "f1480911-0b7a-45a1-a733-cb7ceb4cddd7"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "check_id": "CWE-79",
      "path": "app/app.py",
      "start": {
        "line": 280,
        "col": 1
      },
      "end": {
        "line": 280,
        "col": 100
      },
      "extra": {
        "message": "Reflected XSS via 404 Error Handler URL Rendering\n\nThe `request.url` is directly interpolated into an HTML template string via `%s` string formatting and then rendered with `render_template_string()`. Because the user input is inserted into the template source before Jinja2 processes it, Jinja2's auto-escaping does not apply to this content. An attacker can inject HTML/JavaScript via the URL path, resulting in reflected XSS. For example, visiting a URL containing `<script>alert(1)</script>` would execute JavaScript in the victim's browser.\n\nImpact: An attacker can execute arbitrary JavaScript in the context of a victim's browser session, potentially stealing session tokens, credentials, or performing actions on behalf of the user.\n\nFix: Pass `request.url` as a template variable rather than string-interpolating it into the template source. Use `{{ url }}` in the template with Jinja2 auto-escaping enabled.",
        "severity": "HIGH",
        "metadata": {
          "cwe": [
            "CWE-79"
          ],
          "finding_id": "cc97ca0e-7f0f-4fc3-814f-da81b470938b"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "check_id": "CWE-639",
      "path": "app/app.py",
      "start": {
        "line": 221,
        "col": 1
      },
      "end": {
        "line": 221,
        "col": 100
      },
      "extra": {
        "message": "IDOR on /fetch/customer endpoint - no ownership check\n\nThe /fetch/customer endpoint accepts a customer ID in the request body and returns the full customer record (including credit card number) without verifying that the authenticated user owns or is authorized to access that customer record. Any authenticated user can access any customer's data by providing their ID.\n\nImpact: Any authenticated user can enumerate and access all customer records including PII and credit card numbers by iterating through sequential integer IDs.\n\nFix: Add authorization check to verify the authenticated user has permission to access the requested customer record. Filter queries by the authenticated user's identity.",
        "severity": "HIGH",
        "metadata": {
          "cwe": [
            "CWE-639"
          ],
          "finding_id": "bc34ea8c-82f5-439f-9f03-14e6211a1f91"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "check_id": "CWE-200",
      "path": "app/app.py",
      "start": {
        "line": 260,
        "col": 1
      },
      "end": {
        "line": 260,
        "col": 100
      },
      "extra": {
        "message": "Credit Card Numbers Returned in fetch_customer API Response\n\nThe /fetch/customer endpoint returns credit card numbers in the API response as 'cc_num'. This exposes sensitive financial data to any authenticated user.\n\nImpact: Any authenticated user can retrieve full credit card numbers for any customer, enabling financial fraud.\n\nFix: Mask or redact credit card numbers in API responses (e.g., show only last 4 digits). Implement proper access controls.",
        "severity": "HIGH",
        "metadata": {
          "cwe": [
            "CWE-200"
          ],
          "finding_id": "7a545e6e-397e-4942-850e-8e612e09b44e"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "check_id": "CWE-94",
      "path": "app/app.py",
      "start": {
        "line": 329,
        "col": 1
      },
      "end": {
        "line": 329,
        "col": 100
      },
      "extra": {
        "message": "Unsafe YAML deserialization allows arbitrary code execution\n\nThe `/yaml_hammer` endpoint uses `yaml.load(y)` without specifying a safe Loader. In PyYAML, `yaml.load()` with the default Loader can deserialize arbitrary Python objects, enabling remote code execution.\n\nImpact: An attacker can upload a crafted YAML file that deserializes arbitrary Python objects, leading to remote code execution on the server.\n\nFix: Use `yaml.safe_load(y)` or explicitly specify `yaml.load(y, Loader=yaml.SafeLoader)` to prevent deserialization of arbitrary Python objects.",
        "severity": "HIGH",
        "metadata": {
          "cwe": [
            "CWE-94"
          ],
          "finding_id": "1bf9798e-ff74-4fc6-9625-0abb6dfecaca"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "check_id": "CWE-256",
      "path": "app/app.py",
      "start": {
        "line": 36,
        "col": 1
      },
      "end": {
        "line": 36,
        "col": 100
      },
      "extra": {
        "message": "Plaintext Password Storage in User Model\n\nThe User model stores passwords as plain strings with no hashing applied in the setup_users function (line 63) or the login comparison (line 182). The password column is a plain String(80) and the admin password is stored as plaintext 'admin123'.\n\nImpact: All user passwords are stored in plaintext in the database. Database compromise exposes all credentials.\n\nFix: Hash passwords using bcrypt or argon2 before storage, and compare hashes during login.",
        "severity": "HIGH",
        "metadata": {
          "cwe": [
            "CWE-256"
          ],
          "finding_id": "9885bef0-7c18-40c4-ad15-b825b4bf75d5"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "check_id": "CWE-347",
      "path": "app/app.py",
      "start": {
        "line": 97,
        "col": 1
      },
      "end": {
        "line": 97,
        "col": 100
      },
      "extra": {
        "message": "Insecure JWT verification disables signature validation\n\nThe `insecure_verify` function calls `jwt.decode(token, verify=False)` which disables all JWT signature verification. Any attacker can craft arbitrary JWT tokens that will be accepted as valid.\n\nImpact: An attacker can create arbitrary JWT tokens with any claims (e.g., any user identity) and they will be accepted, completely bypassing authentication for the `/get/<cust_id>` endpoint.\n\nFix: Always verify JWT signatures. Use `jwt.decode(token, key, algorithms=['HS256'], verify=True)` with proper key and algorithm specification.",
        "severity": "HIGH",
        "metadata": {
          "cwe": [
            "CWE-347"
          ],
          "finding_id": "a8489bee-5fc2-44d0-b941-65dbf16a1e5f"
        }
      }
    },
